<ce:para>The behavior of macroscopic systems was predicted using quantum mechanical methods, specifically considering the thermodynamics and kinetics of materials related to hydrogen storage in the solid state. DFT calculations were used to screen over 300 reactions that were not studied experimentally. Several interesting destabilized metal hydrides having favorable thermodynamics were identified. The effect of substitutional alloying on the thermodynamics of different metal hydrides was studied. The kinetics of selected surface reactions on several hydride-related materials using DFT was studied. Calculations indicated that the initial dissociation of H<inf>2</inf> on Mg<inf>2</inf>Si was facile at room temperature and above. However, the calculations also showed that Mg<inf>2</inf>Si was very susceptible to oxidation, which completely passivated the surface toward hydrogen dissociation. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the 2007 AIChE Annual Meeting (Salt Lake City, UT 11/4-9/2007).</ce:para>
